              "textContents": [
                {
                  "paragraphOrdinal": 1,
                  "paragraphImage": "",
                  "paragraphTitle": "Languages",
                  "paragraphSubtitles": [
                    "Look at the sentences from the interview between Mona and Juan and from Use it or lose it? Then use the correct words to complete the definitions (1–5)."
                  ],
                  "paragraphContents": [
                    "They used really strange words and phrases – lots of idioms that I’ve never heard before."
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "paragraphOrdinal": 2,
                  "paragraphImage": "",
                  "paragraphTitle": "",
                  "paragraphSubtitles": null,
                  "paragraphContents": [
                    "Plus, the people had very strong accents, so I couldn’t understand very much at all!"
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "paragraphOrdinal": 3,
                  "paragraphImage": "",
                  "paragraphTitle": "",
                  "paragraphSubtitles": null,
                  "paragraphContents": [
                    "By the end of that year, I spoke Spanish fluently (but not very accurately)."
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "paragraphOrdinal": 4,
                  "paragraphImage": "",
                  "paragraphTitle": "",
                  "paragraphSubtitles": null,
                  "paragraphContents": [
                    "It turns out that bilingual people are much better at activities like this than monolingual people."
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "paragraphOrdinal": 5,
                  "paragraphImage": "",
                  "paragraphTitle": "Definitions",
                  "paragraphSubtitles": null,
                  "paragraphContents": [
                    " 1. If you’re monolingual , you only speak one language; if you’re bilingual , you speak two languages."
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "paragraphOrdinal": 6,
                  "paragraphImage": "",
                  "paragraphTitle": "",
                  "paragraphSubtitles": null,
                  "paragraphContents": [
                    "2. A(n) phrase is a group of two or more words that go together as a unit (e.g. heavy old doors)."
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "paragraphOrdinal": 7,
                  "paragraphImage": "",
                  "paragraphTitle": "",
                  "paragraphSubtitles": null,
                  "paragraphContents": [
                    "3. Your accent is the way you pronounce words. It sometimes shows which part of a country you are from."
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "paragraphOrdinal": 8,
                  "paragraphImage": "",
                  "paragraphTitle": "",
                  "paragraphSubtitles": null,
                  "paragraphContents": [
                    "4. A(n) idiom has its own meaning (e.g. ‘Use it or lose it’). It’s usually hard to figure out the meaning just by looking at the words."
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "paragraphOrdinal": 9,
                  "paragraphImage": "",
                  "paragraphTitle": "",
                  "paragraphSubtitles": null,
                  "paragraphContents": [
                    "5. If you speak fluently, you don’t pause to think in the middle of sentences. If you speak accurately, you don’t make mistakes."
                  ]
                }
              ],
